@page "/changelog"
@layout PublicLayout

<PageTitle>Change Log — Nornis</PageTitle>

<article class="nornis-public-page">
    <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Change Log</div>
    <h1>What's new</h1>

    <section class="nornis-changelog-entry">
        <h2>July 16–20, 2026</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Public world sharing: give a world a public address and switch it on — anyone gets a read-only view of party-visible material only (the codex, the timeline, and session notes), as an anonymous observer. Nothing private or GM-only ever appears, and you can switch it off again at any time.</li>
            <li>Library: keep the sourcebooks, maps, and handouts your table actually references — immutable, indexed PDFs that answer through the Loremaster with page citations, and never become canon.</li>
            <li>Journey map: the party's trail across the map, session by session — drag the playhead to walk the route and surface what each stop meant.</li>
            <li>Session Wrap-Up: after a session lands, a card surfaces what advanced, what's gone quiet, what could nest, and which new arcs need a home — each choice saved the moment you make it.</li>
            <li>Reveal to the party: when the fiction gives a secret away, a GM ticks exactly what the party now learns, and Nornis checks the reveal leaves nothing dangling. One-way, on purpose.</li>
            <li>Handwritten and photo notes: snap an image, get a vision transcription, and run it through extraction — on an infinite ink canvas.</li>
            <li>More ways in: file uploads, a Map source type with placemark pins, and world invitation links that let people join with a role, expiry, and use limit you set.</li>
            <li>Editable session notes with reprocessing and per-item Private visibility, global artifact search, a public features page, and the artifact collection is now the "Codex." Upgraded to .NET 10 under the hood.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="nornis-changelog-entry">
        <h2>July 9–15, 2026</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Sign in with Auth0 — real accounts, with sessions that outlive the access token.</li>
            <li>Timeline: storylines as a branching, git-style tree on a real-world calendar, with a nesting (PartOf) hierarchy and close-outs for arcs that finish.</li>
            <li>The artifact web became an interactive, force-directed graph you can explore and search.</li>
            <li>A GM-only Admin page gathers Settings, Costs, and the processing queue in one place.</li>
            <li>Self-service Profiles: set your display name per world and claim your character.</li>
            <li>Capture gained a TipTap WYSIWYG editor; artifacts gained multi-select filters, sort, rename, and a quick-add box that feeds new information straight through extraction.</li>
            <li>Manual artifact merge to fold duplicates together, plus an AI retrospective that proposes closures for finished storylines.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="nornis-changelog-entry">
        <h2>July 2–8, 2026</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>The app takes shape: the web shell and dashboard, plus the Sources, Capture, Artifacts, Storylines, Canon, Costs, and Settings screens, all wired to the API.</li>
            <li>Ask the Loremaster launched — grounded answers with citations, confidence, and caveats, powered by Azure OpenAI; suggestions drawn from your world's live state.</li>
            <li>Review queue with accept / edit / reject on every AI-proposed change, including "accept all" applied in dependency order.</li>
            <li>Continuity Health: a read on your record's consistency, completeness, groundedness, and recency.</li>
            <li>Worlds became the root concept (renamed from campaigns), holding campaigns and characters within them.</li>
            <li>Went live on Azure (Container Apps + GitHub Actions), with a public landing page and a per-world daily AI budget.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="nornis-changelog-entry">
        <h2>June 2026</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Project begins: the domain model and data layer — worlds, sources, and the artifacts, facts, and storylines derived from them.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</article>
